metadata.description:
Polyvalence is a collection of imaginary architectures.
Polyvalent architectures, parts, and blocks allow for multiple readings over time. Each minted polyvalence token displays various deterministic rare features, layouts, styles, scales and is in constant reconfiguration, endlessly creating polyvalent imaginary architectures.

metadata.name: Sleepless #80
metadata.description:
Sleepless is a generative art project made from p5.js. Inspired by the artist's travels, the project emulates a window view of a distant city at night. Variations include randomization of different window elements (frames and bars) and city elements (buildings, planes and ships). It is also mintable in several foreground and background colors. The colors and dithering were selected to create a charcoal texture.

Press 'S' to download a high res PNG.
Due to the preview image being compressed to fit your window size, the dithering may look different from the high res PNG.

NFTs minted are under the NFT License 2.0 (https://www.nftlicense.org/)

metadata.name: Syzers #366
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

metadata.name: operation 02 #64
metadata.description:
A further extrapolation of my operation 01 piece. Intentional errors are introduced. Per-view randomization is in the speed and size of the drawing of the arcs, and in the placement of the Voronoi points. Each viewing is unique, but each mint is also unique. 

The image draws in its entirety in about 10 seconds. After 20 seconds, it clears, randomizes the placement, and draws again. Full-screen capable.

Three traits describe each individual mint:

Color: There are nine different color palettes, with "Bubblegum" being a 20% likelihood, and all the others 10% likelihood.

Arc: This is the number of elements drawn around each point. There are three possible states, with 300 being a 10% likelihood, 3000 being a 20% likelihood, and 1500 being the default at 70%.

Resolution: This is the number of points in the Voronoi field. There are four candidates, with 2 being the least likely (10%), 3 and 4 having a 20% likelihood of occurring, and 5 being the most common at 50%.

Created in p5.js

metadata.description: This is a re-imagining of my new forms 04: sand spirals mint from hic et nunc in April '21. (https://hen.hicathon.xyz/objkt/68268 ). It has been altered to produce unique mints. All values are equal likelihood, so there is no "rarity" per se; aesthetic value is the only trait that matters.

metadata.name: Lost Twins #189
metadata.description:
Individually, the mints of this token are very simple. Each mint generates half of two cube forms, and each half is assigned random hues (in multiples of 10, from 0 to 360). Collectively as a project, this token challenges the approach of looking for "rarities" in a new way. How the cubes are rendered leaves the possibility for multiple mints to potentially join up on the sides with colors that perfect match each other. Will you find your lost twin?

Made in p5js
Created November 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Reading a book #817
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #228
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.
